## Loss of Quantum Coherence

In the realm of classical physics, when a target body interacts with environmental [photons](/Photon), the average motion of that target body remains largely unaffected by the scattered photons. It’s like a gentle nudge that’s quickly forgotten. But in the quantum world, things are… messier. When photons interact with a target body that exists in a [superposition](/Quantum_superposition) of states, something more profound happens. The scattered photons become [entangled](/Quantum_entanglement) with the target. This entanglement, this intimate quantum connection, effectively disperses the phase coherence – that delicate quantum property that allows for interference – from the target body out into the entire system. The result? The interference pattern, that tell-tale sign of quantum weirdness, becomes unobservable. It’s as if the system’s quantum soul has been spread too thin to be noticed.

This is just one facet of the grand, bewildering tapestry of [Quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics).

